</div><div id="c414">

<p>I&#8217;d have to disagree on your analysis of the &#8220;deserter&#8221; charge. </p>

<p>Moore&#8217;s basis for the charge is that Bush&#8217;s 7-month absence (at best) is more than the 31-day mininum period of being AWOL in the definition of a deserter in the US Army. </p>

<p>However, <b>(1)</b> Bush was not AWOL from active duty, he was on reserve, 
and <b>(2)</b> he wasn&#8217;t serving in the US Army, he was in the National Guard. Vive la difference. </p>

<p>I recommend checking out the 
<a href="http://www.factcheck.org/article.aspx?docID=131">report</a>
 on this matter at the Annenberg Public Policy Center, or 
<a href="http://www.donaldsensing.com/2004_01_01_archive.html#107495313186595111">Donald Sensing&#8217;s</a> post, either of which are very informative.</p>

